======================================================================
PART 1: The Additive-Multiplicative Table
======================================================================

  The fundamental pair (2, 3) generates four numbers via +, *:
    2 + 3 = 5     (additive)
    2 * 3 = 6     (multiplicative)
    2 + 3 + 1 = 6 (hmm, same as product -- THIS IS SPECIAL)
    2^3 = 8       (exponential)
    3^2 = 9       (reverse exponential)

  The COINCIDENCE 2*3 = 2+3+1 is equivalent to:
    2*3 - 2 - 3 = 1
    (2-1)*(3-1) = 1*2 = 2
  More generally: p*q - p - q = (p-1)(q-1) - 1
  For p=2, q=3: (1)(2) - 1 = 1
  This is the ONLY pair of primes where p*q = p+q+1.

  In tournament theory:
    x = 2: the evaluation point (H = I(Omega, 2))
    x+1 = 3: the Galois gap / beta step
    x + (x+1) = 2*x + 1 = 5: the sum
    x * (x+1) = x^2 + x = 6: the product
    5 = 2*3 - 1 (one less than the product!)
    6 = 2*3 = 3! (also the Vandermonde det)

======================================================================
PART 2: I(5) and I(6) -- evaluating at sum and product
======================================================================

  I(x) = 1 + a1*x + a2*x^2
  I(5) = 1 + 5*a1 + 25*a2
  I(6) = 1 + 6*a1 + 36*a2

  KEY: I(5) mod 6 = I(-1) mod 6 (from CRT tower: b=5, b+1=6)
  And I(-1) mod 6 = H mod 6 (since H mod 3 = I(-1) mod 3, H mod 2 = 1)

  Wait: I(-1) mod 6 vs H mod 6. H = I(2).
  I(-1) mod 2 = (1-a1+a2) mod 2. H mod 2 = 1.
  I(-1) mod 3 = H mod 3 (proved).
  So I(-1) mod 6 = CRT(I(-1) mod 2, I(-1) mod 3)
     = CRT(I(-1) mod 2, H mod 3)
  But I(-1) mod 2 may differ from H mod 2 = 1!

  I(-1) mod 2: {0: 252, 1: 248}
  So I(-1) mod 2 != 1 in general. I(-1) mod 6 != H mod 6.

  BUT: I(5) mod 6 = I(-1) mod 6 (since 5 = -1 mod 6)
  This is a DIFFERENT fact from H mod 3 = I(-1) mod 3.
  I(5) mod 6 = I(-1) mod 6: True

  I(5) mod 6 = CRT(I(-1) mod 2, I(-1) mod 3)
             = CRT((1+a1+a2) mod 2, (1-a1+a2) mod 3)
  This is the FULL mod-6 topology, which H mod 6 only partially captures.

  I(5) mod 6: {0: 84, 1: 107, 2: 105, 3: 76, 4: 63, 5: 65}
  H mod 6:    {1: 170, 3: 160, 5: 170}
  I(-1) mod 6: {0: 84, 1: 107, 2: 105, 3: 76, 4: 63, 5: 65}

======================================================================
PART 3: The Taylor shift -- I(2+3) from I(2)
======================================================================

  I(x+h) = I(x) + h*I'(x) + h^2*I''(x)/2
  I(2+3) = I(5) = I(2) + 3*I'(2) + 9*I''(2)/2
  where I'(2) = a1 + 4*a2, I''(2)/2 = a2
  So: I(5) = H + 3*(a1 + 4*a2) + 9*a2 = H + 3*a1 + 21*a2
    a1=36, a2= 6: H= 97, I(5)= 331, Taylor= 331, match=True
    a1=37, a2= 4: H= 91, I(5)= 286, Taylor= 286, match=True
    a1=45, a2= 6: H=115, I(5)= 376, Taylor= 376, match=True
    a1=28, a2= 4: H= 73, I(5)= 241, Taylor= 241, match=True
    a1=32, a2= 4: H= 81, I(5)= 261, Taylor= 261, match=True
    a1=25, a2= 5: H= 71, I(5)= 251, Taylor= 251, match=True
    a1=34, a2= 6: H= 93, I(5)= 321, Taylor= 321, match=True
    a1=30, a2= 4: H= 77, I(5)= 251, Taylor= 251, match=True
    a1=28, a2= 6: H= 81, I(5)= 291, Taylor= 291, match=True
    a1=30, a2= 3: H= 73, I(5)= 226, Taylor= 226, match=True

  I(5) - H = 3*a1 + 21*a2 = 3*(a1 + 7*a2)
  So I(5) - H is ALWAYS divisible by 3!
  And (I(5)-H)/3 = a1 + 7*a2

  At n=7: (I(5)-H)/3 = a1 + 7*a2 = a1 + n*a2
  The weight 7 = n is the number of vertices!

  GENERAL: I(x+h) - I(x) = h*a1 + (2*x*h + h^2)*a2
          = h*(a1 + (2x+h)*a2)
  For x=2, h=3: I(5)-I(2) = 3*(a1 + 7*a2)
  The coefficient 2x+h = 2*2+3 = 7 = n. COINCIDENCE for n=7.

======================================================================
PART 4: I(6) = I(2*3) vs I(2)*I(3) -- additive vs multiplicative
======================================================================

  For a polynomial f(x), f(ab) != f(a)*f(b) in general.
  But the RATIO I(6)/(I(2)*I(3)) is interesting.
    a1=36, a2= 6: I(2)= 97, I(3)=163, I(6)= 433, I(2)*I(3)=15811, I(6)/prod=0.0274
    a1=37, a2= 4: I(2)= 91, I(3)=148, I(6)= 367, I(2)*I(3)=13468, I(6)/prod=0.0272
    a1=45, a2= 6: I(2)=115, I(3)=190, I(6)= 487, I(2)*I(3)=21850, I(6)/prod=0.0223
    a1=28, a2= 4: I(2)= 73, I(3)=121, I(6)= 313, I(2)*I(3)= 8833, I(6)/prod=0.0354
    a1=32, a2= 4: I(2)= 81, I(3)=133, I(6)= 337, I(2)*I(3)=10773, I(6)/prod=0.0313
    a1=25, a2= 5: I(2)= 71, I(3)=121, I(6)= 331, I(2)*I(3)= 8591, I(6)/prod=0.0385
    a1=34, a2= 6: I(2)= 93, I(3)=157, I(6)= 421, I(2)*I(3)=14601, I(6)/prod=0.0288
    a1=30, a2= 4: I(2)= 77, I(3)=127, I(6)= 325, I(2)*I(3)= 9779, I(6)/prod=0.0332
    a1=28, a2= 6: I(2)= 81, I(3)=139, I(6)= 385, I(2)*I(3)=11259, I(6)/prod=0.0342
    a1=30, a2= 3: I(2)= 73, I(3)=118, I(6)= 289, I(2)*I(3)= 8614, I(6)/prod=0.0336

  Multiplicative defect D = I(6) - I(2)*I(3):
  D = (1+6a1+36a2) - (1+2a1+4a2)(1+3a1+9a2)
  Let me expand:
  (1+2a1+4a2)(1+3a1+9a2) = 1 + 3a1 + 9a2 + 2a1 + 6a1^2 + 18a1*a2
                          + 4a2 + 12a1*a2 + 36a2^2
                        = 1 + 5a1 + 13a2 + 6a1^2 + 30a1*a2 + 36a2^2
  I(6) = 1 + 6a1 + 36a2
  D = (1+6a1+36a2) - (1+5a1+13a2+6a1^2+30a1*a2+36a2^2)
    = a1 + 23a2 - 6a1^2 - 30a1*a2 - 36a2^2
    a1=36, a2= 6: D= -15378, check= -15378, match=True
    a1=37, a2= 4: D= -13101, check= -13101, match=True
    a1=45, a2= 6: D= -21363, check= -21363, match=True
    a1=28, a2= 4: D=  -8520, check=  -8520, match=True
    a1=32, a2= 4: D= -10436, check= -10436, match=True
    a1=25, a2= 5: D=  -8260, check=  -8260, match=True
    a1=34, a2= 6: D= -14180, check= -14180, match=True
    a1=30, a2= 4: D=  -9454, check=  -9454, match=True
    a1=28, a2= 6: D= -10874, check= -10874, match=True
    a1=30, a2= 3: D=  -8325, check=  -8325, match=True

  D < 0 for all non-transitive: True
  Product ALWAYS exceeds the 6-evaluation: I(2)*I(3) > I(6)

======================================================================
PART 5: The special identity (2-1)(3-1) = 2
======================================================================

  (p-1)(q-1) = 1 iff p*q = p+q+1
  For primes: only p=2, q=3 satisfy this.
  Consequence: 2*3 - (2+3) = 1, so 6 = 5+1.

  In I(x) terms:
  I(6) - I(5) = a1*(6-5) + a2*(36-25) = a1 + 11*a2

  I(6) - I(5) = a1 + 11*a2
  Compare with: I(3) - I(2) = a1 + 5*a2
  And: I(2) - I(1) = a1 + 3*a2

  General: I(k+1) - I(k) = a1 + (2k+1)*a2
  The step from k to k+1 has weight 2k+1 on a2.

  Step weights:
    I(1)-I(0) = a1 + 1*a2   (weight 1)
    I(2)-I(1) = a1 + 3*a2   (weight 3)
    I(3)-I(2) = a1 + 5*a2   (weight 5)
    I(4)-I(3) = a1 + 7*a2   (weight 7)
    I(5)-I(4) = a1 + 9*a2   (weight 9)
    I(6)-I(5) = a1 + 11*a2   (weight 11)
    I(7)-I(6) = a1 + 13*a2   (weight 13)
    I(8)-I(7) = a1 + 15*a2   (weight 15)
    I(9)-I(8) = a1 + 17*a2   (weight 17)
    I(10)-I(9) = a1 + 19*a2   (weight 19)
    I(11)-I(10) = a1 + 21*a2   (weight 21)
    I(12)-I(11) = a1 + 23*a2   (weight 23)

  The weight at k=2 (I(3)-I(2)) is 5 = 2+3
  The weight at k=5 (I(6)-I(5)) is 11 = our positional 11!
  The weight at k=1 (I(2)-I(1)) is 3 = our fundamental 3!
  The weight at k=4 (I(5)-I(4)) is 9 = 3^2!

======================================================================
PART 6: The step weight 2k+1 and the odd number sequence
======================================================================

  I(k+1) - I(k) = a1 + (2k+1)*a2
  The weights are 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, ...
  These are the ODD NUMBERS = the differences of perfect squares!
  (k+1)^2 - k^2 = 2k+1

  The x^2 term in I(x) means that consecutive differences
  grow as odd numbers. This is the QUADRATIC structure of I.

  Summing steps:
  I(b) - I(0) = sum_{k=0}^{b-1} [a1 + (2k+1)*a2]
              = b*a1 + a2 * sum_{k=0}^{b-1} (2k+1)
              = b*a1 + a2 * b^2
  So I(b) = 1 + b*a1 + b^2*a2. CORRECT by definition.

  The step I(3)-I(2) = a1 + 5*a2 has a dual interpretation:
  It is the coefficient of the FIRST DIFFERENCE at the counting point.
  And 5 = 2+3 = the sum of the fundamental pair.
  The derivative I'(2) = a1 + 4*a2. NOT the same (off by a2).
  Step = derivative + a2. The extra a2 is the 'curvature correction'.
    a1=36, a2= 6: step= 66, deriv= 60, diff=6=a2=6
    a1=37, a2= 4: step= 57, deriv= 53, diff=4=a2=4
    a1=45, a2= 6: step= 75, deriv= 69, diff=6=a2=6
    a1=28, a2= 4: step= 48, deriv= 44, diff=4=a2=4
    a1=32, a2= 4: step= 52, deriv= 48, diff=4=a2=4

======================================================================
PART 7: 10 = 2*(2+3) and 11 = 2*(2+3)+1
======================================================================

  10 = 2 * 5 = 2 * (2+3)
  11 = 2 * 5 + 1 = 2*(2+3) + 1

  10 = x * (x + (x+1)) = x*(2x+1) where x=2
  11 = x*(2x+1) + 1

  In Z[x] at x=2:
    10 = 2x^2 + x = x(2x+1)
    11 = 2x^2 + x + 1 = x(2x+1) + 1

  Note: 2x+1 = 5 is the step weight at k=x=2.
  So 10 = x * (step weight at x)!

  I(10) = 1 + 10*a1 + 100*a2
  I(11) = 1 + 11*a1 + 121*a2
  I(11) - I(10) = a1 + 21*a2 (step weight 2*10+1 = 21 = 3*7)

  Step weight at k=10: 21 = 3 * 7 = 3 * n (at n=7)
  Another n=7 coincidence!

  I(10) and I(11) via Vandermonde extraction:
  I(10) = 1 + 10a1 + 100a2
  I(2) = 1 + 2a1 + 4a2 = H
  I(10) - I(2) = 8a1 + 96a2 = 8*(a1 + 12a2)
  So I(10) = H + 8*(a1 + 12*a2)
  And (I(10) - H)/8 = a1 + 12*a2
    a1=36, a2= 6: (I(10)-H)/8 = 108 = a1+12a2 = 108, match=True
    a1=37, a2= 4: (I(10)-H)/8 = 85 = a1+12a2 = 85, match=True
    a1=45, a2= 6: (I(10)-H)/8 = 117 = a1+12a2 = 117, match=True
    a1=28, a2= 4: (I(10)-H)/8 = 76 = a1+12a2 = 76, match=True
    a1=32, a2= 4: (I(10)-H)/8 = 80 = a1+12a2 = 80, match=True

======================================================================
PART 8: Factorization in Z[x] -- everything through x=2
======================================================================

  Rewriting key numbers in terms of x=2:
      1 = 1                                        [check: 1]
      2 = x                                        [check: 2]
      3 = x+1                                      [check: 3]
      4 = x^2                                      [check: 4]
      5 = x^2+1 = x+(x+1) = 2x+1                   [check: 5]
      6 = x(x+1) = x^2+x                           [check: 6]
      7 = x^3-1 = (x-1)(x^2+x+1) = 1*7             [check: 7]
      8 = x^3                                      [check: 8]
      9 = (x+1)^2                                  [check: 9]
     10 = x(x^2+1) = x(2x+1)                       [check: 10]
     11 = x^3+x+1                                  [check: 11]
     12 = x^2(x+1)                                 [check: 12]
     21 = x^4+x^2+1 = (x^2+x+1)(x^2-x+1) = 7*3     [check: 21]

